  {
    "id": "bank-a-q001",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "volatile-vs-nonvolatile",
    "stem": "Storage which stores or retains data after power off is called-",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Volatile storage",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Non-volatile storage",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Sequential storage",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Direct storage",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Retaining data after power is removed is the definition of non-volatile storage (ROM, hard disk, flash). Volatile storage (RAM) loses its contents when power is cut. Sequential and direct describe how storage is accessed, not whether it survives power off, so they answer a different question.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 1
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "188a4ea3aacf2847ba4aa0ab3d43e254332301d7"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q002",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "rom",
    "stem": "A permanent memory, which halls data and instruction for start-up the computer and does not erase data after power off.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Network interface card",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "CPU",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "RAM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "ROM",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "The start-up (bootstrap/BIOS) instructions must be present the instant power comes on, before anything can be loaded from disk, so they live in ROM, which is non-volatile and permanent. RAM is the trap: it is memory, but it is volatile and empty at power-on.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 2
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "3d15a99f4c0464d0369e1da4bd0bed38e41c7a88"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q003",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "dram",
    "stem": "Which of the following memories must be refreshed many times per second?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "EPROM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "ROM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Static RAM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Dynamic RAM",
        "isCorrect": true
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "Dynamic RAM stores each bit as charge on a tiny capacitor, and that charge leaks away, so every cell must be read and rewritten (refreshed) thousands of times per second. Static RAM holds bits in a flip-flop and needs no refresh; ROM and EPROM are non-volatile and hold their contents with no power at all.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 3
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "400f5dd526cb92b6001d1f662aead10f9df09832"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q004",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "storage-hierarchy",
    "stem": "USB-type storage device is -",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Secondary",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Axillary",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Tertiary",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Primary",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "A USB flash drive holds data outside the CPU's directly addressable main memory and persists it, which makes it secondary (auxiliary) storage. Primary is the trap: primary/main memory means RAM, which the CPU reads directly. 'Axillary' is a misspelling of auxiliary and is not the term the key uses.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 4
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "1594e7442df0769ade4f2beb4fa32485f627be22"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q005",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "general-it",
    "subtopic": "data-hierarchy",
    "stem": "Which of the following places the common data elements in order from smallest to largest?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Character, File, Record, Field, Database, File",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Character, Record, Field, Database, File",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Character, Field, Record, File, Database",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Bit, Byte, Character, Record, Field, File, Database",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "The standard data hierarchy builds upward: character (a single symbol) -> field (a group of characters, e.g. a name) -> record (a group of related fields) -> file (a group of records) -> database (a group of files). Option D is the trap: it starts correctly with bit and byte but then puts Record before Field, which inverts the containment.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 5
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "ac4d44fc86910b75ac63aee95e15de89f6835bd8"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q006",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "backup-media",
    "stem": "Which device is used to back up the data?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Floppy Disk",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Tape",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Network Drive.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of the above",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "Backup only requires a medium that can hold a second copy of the data, and floppy disks, magnetic tape and a network drive all qualify, so 'All of the above' is correct. Tape is the traditional answer and is the trap if you pick a single option; the question asks which device can be used, not which is best.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 6
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "d03584c998b911033d3ea01149b8e7a8c0633168"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q007",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "number-systems",
    "subtopic": "units",
    "stem": "A half byte is known as_____.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "data",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "bit",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "half byte",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "nibble",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "A byte is 8 bits, so half a byte is 4 bits, which is called a nibble. Option C ('half byte') is a restatement of the stem rather than the technical name.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 7
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "398634be5c3ef7aa8c4cc111fe437e5e92f87ac4"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q008",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "main-memory",
    "stem": "Main memory of computer is -",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Internal",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "External",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "(A) and (B)both",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Auxiliary",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Main memory (RAM plus ROM) sits on the motherboard and is directly addressable by the CPU, which makes it internal or primary memory. External/auxiliary refers to secondary storage such as disks and USB drives, which the CPU cannot address directly and must load into main memory first.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 8
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "263aba662bd038012d1d4be896ea5414954a33bf"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q010",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "rom",
    "stem": "What is the permanent memory built into your computer called?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "RAM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "ROM",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "CPU",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "CD-ROM",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Permanent memory built into the machine and readable at power-on is ROM. RAM is volatile so it cannot be permanent, and CD-ROM is the trap: it is read-only but it is removable optical media, not memory built into the computer.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 10
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "8df4d209cdc4d55cb30613e4c1cddfd30210a7c8"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q011",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "optical-media",
    "stem": "With a CD you can...........",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "read",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "write",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "read and write",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
